   <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/news/technology/"> 
      <![CDATA[><p><img hspace="4" height="866" border="0" align="left" width="400" vspace="2" alt="Parking_meter_1.jpg" title="Parking_meter_1.jpg" src="http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/news/technology/Parking_meter_1.jpg" />The New York Times said <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/21/business/media/21times.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss">today they plan to move to a &quot;metered&quot; pay model</a>, where heavy users of the site can be expected to be charged for access depending on the number of stories they click on.  </p><p>The newspaper was careful to publicize the cautious deliberations they went through in making their announcement, which is expected to take effect in January 2011.  </p><p>Indeed, it'll be a closely watched effort.  I have to guess that many, many publishers who've contemplated moving their content behind a paywall may now wait to do so until they see how well the NYTimes does with it. </p><p>News publishers are a notoriously conservative bunch who look to the NY Times and the Wall Street Journal as trend-setters, to a certain extent.   </p><p>Overall, though, I like the Times' idea so far. I think part of the success will depend on how many articles they choose to make freely available to casual users of their site and if they can propose a reasonable price structure for those who may be willing to pay a little for their content.  </p>]]>
      
